@endnode
@node install "  Install and delete"
@font XCourier.font 13

  Read all informations about <mv1440sup72> ! 
  System requirement for the installation: OS 2.04 ++, C/IconX.
  All use is at your own risk. Be sure to have originally ins-
  stalled WB. Tested on A1200, OS 3.0
  -----------------------------------
  
  If you have OS 2.04++ and the configuration of your computer
  conforms with the original WB installation you can use the
  install program to install <mv1440sup72>.
  
 @{fg highlight} * To use the install program whole the directory <mv1440sup72>
    must be in the WB partition of your harddisk!@{fg text}
  
  Using an older version of <mv1440sup72> first delete the old directories
  <mv1440sup72> and <monitorfiles_old> from the workbench partition
  of your harddisk. 
    
  The install programm then checks your WB and stops installation
  when it reads unclear constellations.
  
  Your old monitor settings will be saved in the new WB directory
  <monitorfiles_old>.@{fg highlight} Don`t delete this directory without using
  the delete program. The install+delete programs need this directory
  to work.@{fg text}

  Reset your Amiga to enable the monitor tooltypes, screenmode.prefs
  and the patched overscan.prefs.
  
  It is very useful to new adjust and fix all windowsizes and their
  positions. All your programs with an own screenmode requester should
  also been adjusted to the new mode.
  
  Use the control knobs on the front of your Microvitec to adjust the
  height and the position of the image. Adjust the screen brightness and
  contrast, too.
  
  You can turn down the knob for the height of the image to his left end
  to reduce the difference between monitorlines.
  
  For all your programs with no own screenmode requester use a program that
  patches OpenScreen and OpenScreenTagList of the intuition library, e.g.
  ScreenPatch by Christian Friedel, Hannover. It opens a screen in a
  selected mode.

  You can find ScreenPatch on Aminet cd 5 misc/amag AM9410_2.lha or the
  german Amiga-Magazin-CD 10/95 or download the program from aminet
  misc/amag/AM9410_2.lha 
 
  
  To restore your old monitor settings use <delete_mv1440sup72>.
  All settings of <mv1440sup72> and the directory <monitorfiles_old>
  will be deleted then. 
@endnode
    
  
